modules.description: This module implements session management using MariaDB as the backend. It provides operations to create sessions, set and retrieve session values, and find sessions by identifier. These functions work with session data structures and string key-value pairs, enabling persistent session storage and retrieval in web applications.

This module handles PostgreSQL-specific session migration registration and execution. It provides functions to register individual or multiple migrations, execute them asynchronously, and manage their lifecycle within a container. Concrete use cases include setting up or updating session-related database schemas during application startup.

This module handles database migrations specifically for MariaDB sessions. It provides functions to register individual or multiple migration tasks, execute them asynchronously, and manage their lifecycle within a container. Use it to set up or update session-related database schemas in MariaDB environments.

This module implements session management using PostgreSQL as the backend. It provides functions to create sessions, set and retrieve session values, and find sessions by identifier. Use cases include storing user authentication tokens, tracking user state across requests, and managing temporary session data in web applications.

This module manages sessions with creation, validation, and expiration capabilities, integrating with PostgreSQL and MariaDB for persistent storage. It supports key-value session data operations and provides mechanisms for secure session tracking across server restarts, enabling use cases like user authentication and state persistence in web applications. Submodules handle database-specific session storage and migration workflows, allowing registration, execution, and lifecycle management of schema updates during application startup. For example, sessions can be stored and retrieved using string keys, while migrations ensure database schemas are correctly set up or updated for both PostgreSQL and MariaDB environments.
